- Wheat: 7 × 5 = 35         → 5/1 = 5 per unit

- Ore: 14 × 40 = 560        → 40/1 = 40 per unit  

1. Evaluating Player 0’s new offer  
   Offer: 3 Brick (value 3 × 24 = 72) for 2 Ore (value 2 × 40 = 80)

   - Value I give up: 80  
   - Value I receive: 72  
   Net change = 72 – 80 = –8 (negative) → the trade hurts my total value.  

   Decision: Deny.

2. Making a counter-offer  
   I still want Ore (it has the highest per-unit value) but am willing to part with lower-value resources.  
   My lowest-value resources per unit are Wheat (5) and Wood (11), so I’ll freight my offer with them while keeping overall fairness.

   Proposal: give Player 0 4 Wheat + 2 Wood (value 4×5 + 2×11 = 42) in exchange for 1 Ore (value 40).  
   I’m giving up slightly more value (42 > 40) to increase the chance of acceptance.

[Offer: 4 Wheat, 2 Wood -> 1 Ore]

rounds.response:
Thumbs-up, let’s translate the conversation so far into actual market values (all values per unit):

Wheat: 5  
Wood: 11  
Sheep: 15  
Brick: 24  
Ore: 40  

(1) Opening pattern  
- 5 Wheat (25) + 5 Wood (55) ⇒ 2 Ore (80)  → Net –0 to them, +25 to me if accepted. ‑Rejected by me.

(2–3) They then offered 3 Brick (72) for 2 Ore (80).  Value difference ≈ –8 for them. I judged it barely above parity and preferred to hold Ore. Rejected again.

(4) I offered 4 Wheat (20) + 2 Wood (22) for 1 Ore (40). 42 → 40, almost a dead-even swap (within rounding) and I was happy to lighten Wheat / Wood for the highest-tier good. They accepted.

• After that swap my reserve count is 3 Wheat, 6 Wood, 20 Sheep, 23 Brick, 13 Ore.

(5) Immediately after, they offered 2 Sheep (30) for 1 Ore (40).  Value loss for them is –10, value gain for me +10. Good for me; I accepted.

• Now my reserve is 3 Wheat, 6 Wood, 18 Sheep, 23 Brick, 12 Ore.

Current totals  
Wheat: 3   (15)  
Wood: 6    (66)  
Sheep: 18 (270)  
Brick: 23 (552)  
Ore: 12   (480)  
Pre-game total: 93  
Post-all-trades total: 1383   (a huge +53 boost already from just the two Ore buys)

Their latest bid (turn about to tick forward) is 2 Brick (48) for 1 Ore (40).  An 8-point gap against me. At the margin 8 points of value is basically the same as the last Ore-deal (which was a 10-point gap in my favour).  If I accept, my Ore drops to 11 but my Brick jumps to 25.  Future Ore trades will become scarcer on my side, so it is not attractive in the long run, especially since holding Ore retains high upside.  Therefore:

[Deny]

I am now willing to make my own offer.  I currently have 18 Sheep (270) and 23 Brick (552).  They seem loaded with Ore.  A modest sheep-for-ore swap likely interests them if I surrender slightly above the mathematical value (Ore is the bottleneck resource).  Their last bid only valued Ore at ~24 per unit (2 Brick), so meeting the gap keeps the deal plausible.

[Offer: 5 Sheep -> 1 Ore]
